\begin_layout Abstract
Excitons play a key role in the linear optical response of 2D materials.
 However, their significance in the highly nonlinear optical response to
 intense mid-infrared light has often been overlooked.
 Using hBN as a prototypical example, we theoretically demonstrate that
 excitons play a major role in this process.
 Specifically, we illustrate their formation and stability in intense low-freque
ncy fields, where field strengths surpass the Coulomb field binding the
 electron-hole pair in the exciton.
 Additionally, we establish a parallelism between these results and the
 already-known physics of Rydberg states using an atomic model.
 Finally, we propose an experimental setup to test the effect of excitons
 in the nonlinear optical response
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Emergence is a fundamental concept in condensed matter physics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Anderson1972"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Pertinent examples include superconductivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Keimer2015,Fernandes2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, magnetism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huang2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and topological phases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hasan2010,qi2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another example are excitons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Koch2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: the quasiparticles created by attraction between an electron excited to
 the conduction band and the hole left in the valence band.
 In 2D materials excitons have particularly significant binding energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{E_{{\rm bind}}\sim1}$
\end_inset

 eV and play dominant role in their linear optical response 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wang2018colloquium"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 What should one expect for the highly nonlinear optical response, when
 2D solids interact with intense low-frequency laser fields? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a highly pertinent key question for high harmonic generation (HHG)
 in solids, which has emerged as an important direction in ultrafast condensed
 matter physics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kruchinin2018,Ghimire2018,Goulielmakis2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Will excitons provide strong contribution to intense-field driven nonlinear
 response, or will they simply not survive the strong laser field, which
 typically exceeds the Coulomb field that binds the electron and the hole
 together? Answering this question is important both fundamentally and for
 applications.
 At the fundamental level, HHG offers a unique window into the electronic
 structure and dynamics in trivial, topological, and strongly correlated
 solids far from equilibrium 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ghimire2010,Vampa2015,Luu2015,hawkins2015,wismer2016_yako,tancgone-dejean2017_bandstructure,tancogne-dejean2018_uhubbard,murakami18,Silva2018,Silva2019,chacon20,Uzan2020,Orthodoxou2021,Schmid2021,Ortmann2021,Alcala2022_hightc,Bharti2022,alshafey2022,molinero23"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Interpreting these dynamics without understanding the role of excitons
 is hardly adequate.
 For applications, if excitons can generate bright high harmonics, their
 role would be important when using high harmonics as bright solid-state
 sources of ultrashort VUV-XUV radiation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vampa2017,nourbakshs2021_merdji"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the entry of intense light fields into condensed matter physics is
 relatively recent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ghimire2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, interaction with such fields in general and HHG in particular have been
 extensively studied in atoms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "krausz2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Rydberg states, the atomic analogues of excitons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haug2009quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, were found to play a surprisingly important role in strong-field ionization
 from the ground state (the atomic analogue of electron injection into the
 conduction band.) Prominent examples are the so-called frustrated tunnelling
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yudin2001,nubbemeyer08,eichmann2013,Eichmann2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the Freeman resonances in multi-photon ionization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "freeman1987,Eichmann2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The remarkable stability of Rydberg states against intense laser fields,
 predicted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fedorov1989,Fedorov1990,Fedorov2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, was confirmed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBoer1993_hgmuller,deBoer1994_hgmuller"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, dramatically demonstrated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "eichmann2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and even led to lasing during laser filamentation in dense nitrogen gas
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Richter2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Multiphoton Rydberg excitations have been found to contribute to harmonic
 emission during the laser pulse 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Toma1999,beaulieu2016,mayer2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and free induction decay after its end 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "beaulieu2017_mairesse,bengs2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast, apart from the pioneering works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tancogne-dejean2018_uhubbard,ikemachi2018,udono2022,jensen2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the role of excitons in the strong field regime has been generally ignored,
 with in-depth analysis of their dynamics and the physics of their creation
 and destruction in strong laser fields lacking until now.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work we aim to fill this gap.
 We show that high harmonic emission can reveal the formation of excitons
 by both significantly increasing both the overall harmonic yield, by about
 an order of magnitude, and the emission intensity at energies near excitonic
 excitations, by an even stronger two orders of magnitude.
 We also show that shifting the exciton binding energy by using a substrate
 provides a tell-tale sign of their contributions.
 Time-resolved analysis of the emission shows the formation dynamics and
 the remarkable stability of excitons against strong light fields.
 In spite of the emergent, interaction-induced nature of excitons, we consistent
ly find strong similarity in their strong field dynamics with that of single-par
ticle Rydberg states.
 This connection highlights how a non-trivial emergent quasiparticle, such
 as an exciton in a sea of interacting electrons, can behave much like a
 single-particle excitation in an atomic gas, even when driven by an intense
 field.
\end_layout

