\begin_layout Section*
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, the effect of many-body interactions on the high-harmonic
 spectra of two-dimensional materials has been studied.
 The results shows a significant increase in the emission spectra when accountin
g for these interactions, which is associated to the presence of excitonic
 states within the system.
 Specifically, the enhancement is located at the energy difference between
 the valence band and the first excitonic state; the excitons act as extra
 channels for the tunneling processes from the valence to the conduction
 band.
 Furthermore, we proposed an experimental setup to effectively test the
 effect of excitons.
 Additionally, we have shown that the exciton does survive such strong pulses,
 in complete analogy with the physics observed in atoms due to the Rydberg
 states.
 Finally, we developed a one-dimensional atomic model to gain physical insight.
 Using this model, we showed the same qualitative physics appears in both
 systems: the presence of excited states between a fixed ground state and
 a continuum leads to an enhancement in the high-harmonic spectra.
 Our work has shown how interactions affect the high-harmonic generation
 in two-dimensional materials and the role of emergent quasiparticles.
 These results allow us to reinterpret the excitons as a many-body version
 of Rydberg states in the strong field regime, opening the window for the
 use of the techniques in atomic strong field physics for imaging and control
 of these Rydberg states in the context of condensed matter targets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
hBN simulations –
\emph default
 The microscopic response of the system to the laser field was obtained
 by numerically solving the Semiconductor Bloch Equations (SBEs) in the
 Wannier Gauge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silva2019_wannier,cistaro2023_edus"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These equations, in atomic units, reads
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{i}\partial_{t}\rho_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k},t)=[H^{(0)}(\boldsymbol{k})+\text{\ensuremath{\Sigma}}(\boldsymbol{k},t),\rho(\boldsymbol{k},t)]_{nm}\\
+|e|\boldsymbol{E}(t)\cdot[\boldsymbol{A}(\boldsymbol{k}),\rho(\boldsymbol{k},t)]_{nm}\\
+\text{i}|e|\boldsymbol{E}(t)\cdot\nabla_{\boldsymbol{k}}\rho_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k},t)
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{nm}^{(0)}(\boldsymbol{k})$
\end_inset

 are the non-interacting terms of the Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\Sigma_{nm}}}(\boldsymbol{k},t)$
\end_inset

 accounts for the electronic Coulomb interactions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k})$
\end_inset

 are the multiband Berry connection terms and 
\begin_inset Formula $n,\,m$
\end_inset

 refers to the band indexes.
 The electronic interaction are incorporated in the dynamics at the Fock
 level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ridolfi2020expeditious,cistaro2023_edus"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More formally, this means that the self-energy is calculated using
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{\ensuremath{\Sigma_{nm}}}(\boldsymbol{k},t)=-\sum_{\boldsymbol{k'}}V_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{k'})\left(\rho_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k}',t)-\rho_{nm}^{0}\right).
\]

\end_inset

where the initial state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{nm}^{0}=\rho_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k},0)$
\end_inset

, is completely filled for all the states below the Fermi energy.
 The subtraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k}',t)-\rho_{nm}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is done to ensure that we not take into account interactions in the equilibrium
 state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{k'})$
\end_inset

, reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{nm}(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{k'})=\sum_{\boldsymbol{G}}e^{i(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{k'}+\boldsymbol{G})\cdot(\boldsymbol{\tau}_{n}-\boldsymbol{\tau}_{m})}V(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{k'}+\boldsymbol{G}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the center of the Wannier orbitals and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 are the vectors of the reciprocal lattice.
 The sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 is done to ensure the periodicity of the system.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\boldsymbol{q})$
\end_inset

, is the Fourier transform of the Rytova-Keldysh potential, which is known
 to accurately capture screening and dielectric effects in two-dimensional
 materials 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Keldysh79,cudazzo11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the monolayer hBN, we used the tight-binding model in which only the
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{z}$
\end_inset

 orbitals are considered 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guinea09-review,silva2019_wannier,cistaro2023_edus"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The hopping parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

, was set to 
\begin_inset Formula $-2.8$
\end_inset

 eV and the on-site energy for the two atomic species was set to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{B/N}=\pm2.26$
\end_inset

 eV.
 The density matrix was constructed in a 
\begin_inset Formula $300\times300$
\end_inset

 Monkhorst–Pack grid and it was time-propagated using a fourth-order Runge-Kutta
 with a timestep of 
\begin_inset Formula $dt=0.1$
\end_inset

 atomic units (au).
 Convergence was ensured for all the numerical parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Atomic model –
\emph default
 The atomic model is based on the solution of the time-dependent Schrödinger
 equation (TDSE) for a one-dimensional atom in the presence of a strong
 laser field.
 In atomic units, the TDSE reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\partial_{t}\Psi(x,t)=\Big(T_{{\rm kin}}+V_{\alpha,\beta}(x)+E(t)\cdot x\Big)\,\Psi(x,t),\label{eq:tdse-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{{\rm kin}}$
\end_inset

is the electronic kinetic energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\alpha,\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 is the softcore potential (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:softcore"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $E(t)$
\end_inset

 is the electric field.
 The TDSE was solved numerically using a fourth-order Runge-Kutta method
 with a timestep of 
\begin_inset Formula $dt=0.1$
\end_inset

 au.
 The initial state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(x,0)$
\end_inset

, was selected as the ground state of the time-independent hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H=T_{{\rm kin}}+V_{\alpha,\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 The calculations were performed in a box of length 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1000$
\end_inset

 au with a grid spacing of 
\begin_inset Formula $dx=0.25$
\end_inset

 au.
 We checked that convergence was achieved for all numerical parameters.
 
\end_layout

